# nl-rag distilled facts ‚Äî domain: eigenvalue-algorithms
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] This article covers the basic idea of the algorithm as originally proposed by Cuppen in 1981, which is not numerically stable without additional refinements.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] As with most eigenvalue algorithms for Hermitian matrices, divide-and-conquer begins with a reduction to tridiagonal form.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] For an $m\times m$ matrix, the standard method for this, via Householder reflections, takes ${\frac {4}{3}}m^{3}$ floating point operations, or ${\frac {8}{3}}m^{3}$ if eigenvectors are needed as well.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] There are other algorithms, such as the Arnoldi iteration, which may do better for certain classes of matrices; we will not consider this further here.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] In certain cases, it is possible to *deflate* an eigenvalue problem into smaller problems.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The eigenvalues and eigenvectors of T are simply those of $T_{1}$ and $T_{2}$ , and it will almost always be faster to solve these two smaller problems than to solve the original problem all at once.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] This technique can be used to improve the efficiency of many eigenvalue algorithms, but it has special significance to divide-and-conquer.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] For the rest of this article, we will assume the input to the divide-and-conquer algorithm is an $m\times m$ real symmetric tridiagonal matrix T .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The algorithm can be modified for Hermitian matrices.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The *divide* part of the divide-and-conquer algorithm comes from the realization that a tridiagonal matrix is "almost" block diagonal.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The size of submatrix $T_{1}$ we will call $n\times n$ , and then $T_{2}$ is $(m-n)\times (m-n)$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] T is almost block diagonal regardless of how n is chosen.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] For efficiency we typically choose $n\approx m/2$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] This can be accomplished with recursive calls to the divide-and-conquer algorithm, although practical implementations often switch to the implicitly shifted QR algorithm for small enough submatrices.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The *conquer* part of the algorithm is the unintuitive part.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] Given the diagonalizations of the submatrices, calculated above, how do we find the diagonalization of the original matrix?
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The remaining task has been reduced to finding the eigenvalues of a diagonal matrix plus a rank-one correction.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] Before showing how to do this, let us simplify the notation.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] We are looking for the eigenvalues of the matrix $D+ww^{T}$ , where D is diagonal with distinct entries and w is any vector with nonzero entries.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The case of a zero entry is simple, since if wi is zero, ( $e_{i}$ ,di) is an eigenpair ( $e_{i}$ is in the standard basis) of $D+ww^{T}$ since $(D+ww^{T})e_{i}=De_{i}=d_{i}e_{i}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] where q is the corresponding eigenvector.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] Keep in mind that $w^{T}q$ is a nonzero scalar.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] If $w^{T}q$ were to be zero, q would be an eigenvector of D by $(D+ww^{T})q=\lambda q$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] If that were the case, q would contain only one nonzero position since D is distinct diagonal and thus the inner product $w^{T}q$ can not be zero after all.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] This equation is known as the *secular equation*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The problem has therefore been reduced to finding the roots of the rational function defined by the left-hand side of this equation.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] Solving the nonlinear secular equation can be done using an iterative technique, such as the Newton‚ÄìRaphson method.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] However, each root can be found in O(1) iterations, each of which requires $\Theta (m)$ flops (for an m -degree rational function), making the cost of the iterative part of this algorithm $\Theta (m^{2})$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The fast multipole method has also been employed to solve the secular equation in $\Theta (m\log(m))$ operations.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] W will use the master theorem for divide-and-conquer recurrences to analyze the running time.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] Remember that above we stated we choose $n\approx m/2$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] In the notation of the Master theorem, $a=b=2$ and thus $\log _{b}a=1$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] Above, we pointed out that reducing a Hermitian matrix to tridiagonal form takes ${\frac {4}{3}}m^{3}$ flops.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] This dwarfs the running time of the divide-and-conquer part, and at this point it is not clear what advantage the divide-and-conquer algorithm offers over the QR algorithm (which also takes $\Theta (m^{2})$ flops for tridiagonal matrices).
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The advantage of divide-and-conquer comes when eigenvectors are needed as well.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] If this is the case, reduction to tridiagonal form takes ${\frac {8}{3}}m^{3}$ , but the second part of the algorithm takes $\Theta (m^{3})$ as well.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] For the QR algorithm with a reasonable target precision, this is $\approx 6m^{3}$ , whereas for divide-and-conquer it is $\approx {\frac {4}{3}}m^{3}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The reason for this improvement is that in divide-and-conquer, the $\Theta (m^{3})$ part of the algorithm (multiplying Q matrices) is separate from the iteration, whereas in QR, this must occur in every iterative step.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] Adding the ${\frac {8}{3}}m^{3}$ flops for the reduction, the total improvement is from $\approx 9m^{3}$ to $\approx 4m^{3}$ flops.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] Practical use of the divide-and-conquer algorithm has shown that in most realistic eigenvalue problems, the algorithm actually does better than this.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The reason is that very often the matrices Q and the vectors z tend to be *numerically sparse*, meaning that they have many entries with values smaller than the floating point precision, allowing for *numerical deflation*, i.e. breaking the problem into uncoupled subproblems.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The algorithm presented here is the simplest version.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] In many practical implementations, more complicated rank-1 corrections are used to guarantee stability; some variants even use rank-2 corrections.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] There exist specialized root-finding techniques for rational functions that may do better than the Newton-Raphson method in terms of both performance and stability.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] These can be used to improve the iterative part of the divide-and-conquer algorithm.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/divide-and-conquer-eigenvalue-algorithm] The divide-and-conquer algorithm is readily parallelized, and linear algebra computing packages such as LAPACK contain high-quality parallel implementations.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] In numerical analysis, one of the most important problems is designing efficient and stable algorithms for finding the eigenvalues of a matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] These **eigenvalue algorithms** may also find eigenvectors.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] where **v** is a nonzero *n* √ó 1 column vector, *I* is the *n* √ó *n* identity matrix, *k* is a positive integer, and both *Œª* and **v** are allowed to be complex even when *A* is real.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] When *k* = 1, the vector is called simply an *eigenvector*, and the pair is called an *eigenpair*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Any eigenvalue *Œª* of *A* has ordinary eigenvectors associated to it, for if *k* is the smallest integer such that (*A* ‚àí *ŒªI*)*k* **v** = 0 for a generalized eigenvector **v**, then (*A* ‚àí *ŒªI*)*k*‚àí1 **v** is an ordinary eigenvector.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The value *k* can always be taken as less than or equal to *n*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] In particular, (*A* ‚àí *ŒªI*)*n* **v** = 0 for all generalized eigenvectors **v** associated with *Œª*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] For each eigenvalue Œª of *A*, the kernel ker(*A* ‚àí *ŒªI*) consists of all eigenvectors associated with *Œª* (along with 0), called the *eigenspace* of *Œª*, while the vector space ker((*A* ‚àí *ŒªI*)*n*) consists of all generalized eigenvectors, and is called the *generalized eigenspace*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The *geometric multiplicity* of *Œª* is the dimension of its eigenspace.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The *algebraic multiplicity* of *Œª* is the dimension of its generalized eigenspace.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] where det is the determinant function, the *Œª**i* are all the distinct eigenvalues of *A* and the *Œ±**i* are the corresponding algebraic multiplicities.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The function *pA*(*z*) is the *characteristic polynomial* of *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] So the algebraic multiplicity is the multiplicity of the eigenvalue as a zero of the characteristic polynomial.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Since any eigenvector is also a generalized eigenvector, the geometric multiplicity is less than or equal to the algebraic multiplicity.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The algebraic multiplicities sum up to *n*, the degree of the characteristic polynomial.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The equation *pA*(*z*) = 0 is called the *characteristic equation*, as its roots are exactly the eigenvalues of *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] By the Cayley‚ÄìHamilton theorem, *A* itself obeys the same equation: *pA*(*A*) = 0.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] As a consequence, the columns of the matrix ${\textstyle \prod _{i\neq j}(A-\lambda _{i}I)^{\alpha _{i}}}$ must be either 0 or generalized eigenvectors of the eigenvalue *Œª**j*, since they are annihilated by $(A-\lambda _{j}I)^{\alpha _{j}}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] In fact, the column space is the generalized eigenspace of *Œª**j*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Any collection of generalized eigenvectors of distinct eigenvalues is linearly independent, so a basis for all of **C***n* can be chosen consisting of generalized eigenvectors.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] More generally, if *W* is any invertible matrix, and *Œª* is an eigenvalue of *A* with generalized eigenvector **v**, then (*W*‚àí1*AW* ‚àí *ŒªI*)*k* *W*‚àí*k***v** = 0.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Thus *Œª* is an eigenvalue of *W*‚àí1*AW* with generalized eigenvector *W*‚àí*k***v**.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] That is, similar matrices have the same eigenvalues.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The adjoint *M** of a complex matrix *M* is the transpose of the conjugate of *M*: *M* * = *M* T.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] A square matrix *A* is called *normal* if it commutes with its adjoint: *A***A* = *AA**.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] It is called *Hermitian* if it is equal to its adjoint: *A** = *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] If *A* has only real elements, then the adjoint is just the transpose, and *A* is Hermitian if and only if it is symmetric.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] When applied to column vectors, the adjoint can be used to define the canonical inner product on **C***n*: **w** ‚ãÖ **v** = **w*** **v**.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] It is possible for a real or complex matrix to have all real eigenvalues without being Hermitian.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] For example, a real triangular matrix has its eigenvalues along its diagonal, but in general is not symmetric.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Any problem of numeric calculation can be viewed as the evaluation of some function *f* for some input *x*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The condition number *Œ∫*(*f*, *x*) of the problem is the ratio of the relative error in the function's output to the relative error in the input, and varies with both the function and the input.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The condition number describes how error grows during the calculation.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Its base-10 logarithm tells how many fewer digits of accuracy exist in the result than existed in the input.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The condition number is a best-case scenario.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] It reflects the instability built into the problem, regardless of how it is solved.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] No algorithm can ever produce more accurate results than indicated by the condition number, except by chance.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] However, a poorly designed algorithm may produce significantly worse results.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] For example, as mentioned below, the problem of finding eigenvalues for normal matrices is always well-conditioned.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] However, the problem of finding the roots of a polynomial can be very ill-conditioned.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Thus eigenvalue algorithms that work by finding the roots of the characteristic polynomial can be ill-conditioned even when the problem is not.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] For the problem of solving the linear equation *A***v** = **b** where *A* is invertible, the matrix condition number *Œ∫*(*A*‚àí1, **b**) is given by ||*A*||op||*A*‚àí1||op, where || ||op is the operator norm subordinate to the normal Euclidean norm on **C***n*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Since this number is independent of **b** and is the same for *A* and *A*‚àí1, it is usually just called the condition number *Œ∫*(*A*) of the matrix *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] This value *Œ∫*(*A*) is also the absolute value of the ratio of the largest singular value of *A* to its smallest.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] For general matrices, the operator norm is often difficult to calculate.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] For this reason, other matrix norms are commonly used to estimate the condition number.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] For the eigenvalue problem, Bauer and Fike proved that if *Œª* is an eigenvalue for a diagonalizable *n* √ó *n* matrix *A* with eigenvector matrix *V*, then the absolute error in calculating *Œª* is bounded by the product of *Œ∫*(*V*) and the absolute error in *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Thus the eigenvalue problem for all normal matrices is well-conditioned.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The condition number for the problem of finding the eigenspace of a normal matrix *A* corresponding to an eigenvalue *Œª* has been shown to be inversely proportional to the minimum distance between *Œª* and the other distinct eigenvalues of *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] In particular, the eigenspace problem for normal matrices is well-conditioned for isolated eigenvalues.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] When eigenvalues are not isolated, the best that can be hoped for is to identify the span of all eigenvectors of nearby eigenvalues.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The most reliable and most widely used algorithm for computing eigenvalues is John G.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Kublanovskaya's QR algorithm, considered one of the top ten algorithms of 20th century.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Any monic polynomial is the characteristic polynomial of its companion matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Therefore, a general algorithm for finding eigenvalues could also be used to find the roots of polynomials.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The Abel‚ÄìRuffini theorem shows that any such algorithm for dimensions greater than 4 must either be infinite, or involve functions of greater complexity than elementary arithmetic operations and fractional powers.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] For this reason algorithms that exactly calculate eigenvalues in a finite number of steps only exist for a few special classes of matrices.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] For general matrices, algorithms are iterative, producing better approximate solutions with each iteration.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Some algorithms produce every eigenvalue, others will produce a few, or only one.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] However, even the latter algorithms can be used to find all eigenvalues.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Once an eigenvalue *Œª* of a matrix *A* has been identified, it can be used to either direct the algorithm towards a different solution next time, or to reduce the problem to one that no longer has *Œª* as a solution.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Redirection is usually accomplished by shifting: replacing *A* with *A* ‚àí *ŒºI* for some constant *Œº*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The eigenvalue found for *A* ‚àí *ŒºI* must have *Œº* added back in to get an eigenvalue for *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] For example, for power iteration, *Œº* = *Œª*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Power iteration finds the largest eigenvalue in absolute value, so even when *Œª* is only an approximate eigenvalue, power iteration is unlikely to find it a second time.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Conversely, inverse iteration based methods find the lowest eigenvalue, so *Œº* is chosen well away from *Œª* and hopefully closer to some other eigenvalue.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Reduction can be accomplished by restricting *A* to the column space of the matrix *A* ‚àí *ŒªI*, which *A* carries to itself.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Since *A* - *ŒªI* is singular, the column space is of lesser dimension.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The eigenvalue algorithm can then be applied to the restricted matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] This process can be repeated until all eigenvalues are found.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] If an eigenvalue algorithm does not produce eigenvectors, a common practice is to use an inverse iteration based algorithm with *Œº* set to a close approximation to the eigenvalue.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] This will quickly converge to the eigenvector of the closest eigenvalue to *Œº*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] For small matrices, an alternative is to look at the column space of the product of *A* ‚àí *Œª*'*I* for each of the other eigenvalues *Œª*'.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] A formula for the norm of unit eigenvector components of normal matrices was discovered by Robert Thompson in 1966 and rediscovered independently by several others.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] If $p,p_{j}$ are the characteristic polynomials of A and $A_{j}$ , the formula can be re-written as $|v_{i,j}|^{2}={\frac {p_{j}(\lambda _{i}(A))}{p'(\lambda _{i}(A))}}$ assuming the derivative $p'$ is not zero at $\lambda _{i}(A)$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Because the eigenvalues of a triangular matrix are its diagonal elements, for general matrices there is no finite method like gaussian elimination to convert a matrix to triangular form while preserving eigenvalues.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] But it is possible to reach something close to triangular.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] An upper Hessenberg matrix is a square matrix for which all entries below the subdiagonal are zero.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] A lower Hessenberg matrix is one for which all entries above the superdiagonal are zero.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Matrices that are both upper and lower Hessenberg are tridiagonal.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Hessenberg and tridiagonal matrices are the starting points for many eigenvalue algorithms because the zero entries reduce the complexity of the problem.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Several methods are commonly used to convert a general matrix into a Hessenberg matrix with the same eigenvalues.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] If the original matrix was symmetric or Hermitian, then the resulting matrix will be tridiagonal.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] When only eigenvalues are needed, there is no need to calculate the similarity matrix, as the transformed matrix has the same eigenvalues.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] If eigenvectors are needed as well, the similarity matrix may be needed to transform the eigenvectors of the Hessenberg matrix back into eigenvectors of the original matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] For symmetric tridiagonal eigenvalue problems all eigenvalues (without eigenvectors) can be computed numerically in time O(n log(n)), using bisection on the characteristic polynomial.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Iterative algorithms solve the eigenvalue problem by producing sequences that converge to the eigenvalues.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Some algorithms also produce sequences of vectors that converge to the eigenvectors.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Most commonly, the eigenvalue sequences are expressed as sequences of similar matrices which converge to a triangular or diagonal form, allowing the eigenvalues to be read easily.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The eigenvector sequences are expressed as the corresponding similarity matrices.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] While there is no simple algorithm to directly calculate eigenvalues for general matrices, there are numerous special classes of matrices where eigenvalues can be directly calculated.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Since the determinant of a triangular matrix is the product of its diagonal entries, if *T* is triangular, then ${\textstyle \det(\lambda I-T)=\prod _{i}(\lambda -T_{ii})}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Thus the eigenvalues of *T* are its diagonal entries.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] If *p* is any polynomial and *p*(*A*) = 0, then the eigenvalues of *A* also satisfy the same equation.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] If *p* happens to have a known factorization, then the eigenvalues of *A* lie among its roots.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] For example, a projection is a square matrix *P* satisfying *P*2 = *P*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The roots of the corresponding scalar polynomial equation, *Œª*2 = *Œª*, are 0 and 1.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Thus any projection has 0 and 1 for its eigenvalues.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The multiplicity of 0 as an eigenvalue is the nullity of *P*, while the multiplicity of 1 is the rank of *P*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Another example is a matrix *A* that satisfies *A*2 = *Œ±*2*I* for some scalar *Œ±*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The column spaces of *P*+ and *P*‚àí are the eigenspaces of *A* corresponding to +*Œ±* and ‚àí*Œ±*, respectively.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] For dimensions 2 through 4, formulas involving radicals exist that can be used to find the eigenvalues.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] While a common practice for 2√ó2 and 3√ó3 matrices, for 4√ó4 matrices the increasing complexity of the root formulas makes this approach less attractive.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] From this it follows that the calculation is well-conditioned if the eigenvalues are isolated.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Eigenvectors can be found by exploiting the Cayley‚ÄìHamilton theorem.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Assuming neither matrix is zero, the columns of each must include eigenvectors for the other eigenvalue.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] In both matrices, the columns are multiples of each other, so either column can be used.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Thus, (1, ‚àí2) can be taken as an eigenvector associated with the eigenvalue -2, and (3, ‚àí1) as an eigenvector associated with the eigenvalue 3, as can be verified by multiplying them by *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] This equation may be solved using the methods of Cardano or Lagrange, but an affine change to *A* will simplify the expression considerably, and lead directly to a trigonometric solution.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] If *A* = *pB* + *qI*, then *A* and *B* have the same eigenvectors, and *Œ≤* is an eigenvalue of *B* if and only if *Œ±* = *pŒ≤* + *q* is an eigenvalue of *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The substitution *Œ≤* = 2cos *Œ∏* and some simplification using the identity cos 3*Œ∏* = 4cos3 *Œ∏* ‚àí 3cos *Œ∏* reduces the equation to cos 3*Œ∏* = det(*B*) / 2.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] If det(*B*) is complex or is greater than 2 in absolute value, the arccosine should be taken along the same branch for all three values of *k*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Once again, the eigenvectors of *A* can be obtained by recourse to the Cayley‚ÄìHamilton theorem.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Thus the columns of the product of any two of these matrices will contain an eigenvector for the third eigenvalue.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Thus the *generalized* eigenspace of *Œ±*1 is spanned by the columns of *A* ‚àí *Œ±*2*I* while the ordinary eigenspace is spanned by the columns of (*A* ‚àí *Œ±*1*I*)(*A* ‚àí *Œ±*2*I*).
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The ordinary eigenspace of *Œ±*2 is spanned by the columns of (*A* ‚àí *Œ±*1*I*)2.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] with eigenvalues 1 (of multiplicity 2) and -1.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Thus (‚àí4, ‚àí4, 4) is an eigenvector for ‚àí1, and (4, 2, ‚àí2) is an eigenvector for 1.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] (2, 3, ‚àí1) and (6, 5, ‚àí3) are both generalized eigenvectors associated with 1, either one of which could be combined with (‚àí4, ‚àí4, 4) and (4, 2, ‚àí2) to form a basis of generalized eigenvectors of *A*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Once found, the eigenvectors can be normalized if needed.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] If a 3√ó3 matrix A is normal, then the cross-product can be used to find eigenvectors.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] If $\lambda$ is an eigenvalue of A , then the null space of $A-\lambda I$ is perpendicular to its column space.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] The cross product of two independent columns of $A-\lambda I$ will be in the null space.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] That is, it will be an eigenvector associated with $\lambda$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Since the column space is two dimensional in this case, the eigenspace must be one dimensional, so any other eigenvector will be parallel to it.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] If $A-\lambda I$ does not contain two independent columns but is not **0**, the cross-product can still be used.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] In this case $\lambda$ is an eigenvalue of multiplicity 2, so any vector perpendicular to the column space will be an eigenvector.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Suppose $\mathbf {v}$ is a non-zero column of $A-\lambda I$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Choose an arbitrary vector $\mathbf {u}$ not parallel to $\mathbf {v}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] Then $\mathbf {v} \times \mathbf {u}$ and $(\mathbf {v} \times \mathbf {u} )\times \mathbf {v}$ will be perpendicular to $\mathbf {v}$ and thus will be eigenvectors of $\lambda$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/eigenvalue-algorithm] This does not work when A is not normal, as the null space and column space do not need to be perpendicular for such matrices.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] In linear algebra, a **Householder transformation** (also known as a **Householder reflection** or **elementary reflector**) is a linear transformation that describes a reflection about a plane or hyperplane containing the origin.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] The Householder transformation was used in a 1958 paper by Alston Scott Householder.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] Such an operator is linear and self-adjoint.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] If $V=\mathbb {C} ^{n}$ , note that the reflection hyperplane can be defined by its *normal vector*, a unit vector ${\textstyle {\vec {v}}\in V}$ (a vector with length ${\textstyle 1}$ ) that is orthogonal to the hyperplane.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] where ${\vec {x}}$ is the vector from the origin to the point x , and ${\textstyle {\vec {v}}^{*}}$ is the conjugate transpose of ${\textstyle {\vec {v}}}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] is known as the **Householder matrix**, where ${\textstyle I}$ is the identity matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] which corresponds to reflecting the vector across the line $y=-x$ , which our original vector ${\vec {v}}$ is normal to.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] In geometric optics, specular reflection can be expressed in terms of the Householder matrix (see *Specular reflection ¬ß Vector formulation*).
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] Note that representing a Householder matrix requires only the entries of a single vector, not of an entire matrix (which in most algorithms is never explicitly formed), thereby minimizing the required storage and memory references needed to use them.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] Further, multiplying a Householder matrix by a vector does not involve a full matrix-vector multiplication, but rather only one vector dot product, and then one axpy operation.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] This means its arithmetic complexity is of the same order of **two** low-level BLAS-1 operations.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] Therefore, Householder matrices are extremely arithmetically efficient.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] Where $\vert \vert \Delta P\vert \vert _{F}\leq {\tilde {\gamma _{n}}}:={\frac {cnu}{1-cnu}}$ (where u is unit roundoff, n the size of the matrix P , and c some small constant).
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] In other words, multiplications by Householder matrices are also extremely backwards stable.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] They are also widely used for transforming to a Hessenberg form.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] For symmetric or Hermitian matrices, the symmetry can be preserved, resulting in tridiagonalization.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] Householder transformations can be used to calculate a QR decomposition.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] Thinking geometrically, we are looking for a plane so that the reflection about this plane happens to land directly on the basis vector.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] This procedure is presented in Numerical Analysis by Burden and Faires, and works when the matrix is symmetric.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] In the non-symmetric case, it is still useful as a similar procedure can result in a Hessenberg matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] It uses a slightly altered $\operatorname {sgn}$ function with $\operatorname {sgn} (0)=1$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] Continuing in this manner, the tridiagonal and symmetric matrix is formed.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] In this example, also from Burden and Faires, the given matrix is transformed to the similar tridiagonal matrix A3 by using the Householder method.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] As we can see, the final result is a tridiagonal symmetric matrix which is similar to the original one.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] The process is finished after two steps.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] As unitary matrices are useful in quantum computation, and Householder transformations are unitary, they are very useful in quantum computing.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] The Householder transformation is a reflection about a hyperplane with unit normal vector ${\textstyle v}$ , as stated earlier.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] An ${\textstyle N}$ -by- ${\textstyle N}$ unitary transformation ${\textstyle U}$ satisfies ${\textstyle UU^{*}=I}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] Taking the determinant ( ${\textstyle N}$ -th power of the geometric mean) and trace (proportional to arithmetic mean) of a unitary matrix reveals that its eigenvalues ${\textstyle \lambda _{i}}$ have unit modulus.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] Since arithmetic and geometric means are equal if the variables are constant (see inequality of arithmetic and geometric means), we establish the claim of unit modulus.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] For the case of real valued unitary matrices we obtain orthogonal matrices, ${\textstyle UU^{\textsf {T}}=I}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] It follows rather readily (see Orthogonal matrix) that any orthogonal matrix can be decomposed into a product of 2-by-2 rotations, called Givens rotations, and Householder reflections.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] This is appealing intuitively since multiplication of a vector by an orthogonal matrix preserves the length of that vector, and rotations and reflections exhaust the set of (real valued) geometric operations that render invariant a vector's length.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] The Householder transformation was shown to have a one-to-one relationship with the canonical coset decomposition of unitary matrices defined in group theory, which can be used to parametrize unitary operators in a very efficient manner.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] Finally we note that a single Householder transform, unlike a solitary Givens transform, can act on all columns of a matrix, and as such exhibits the lowest computational cost for QR decomposition and tridiagonalization.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] The penalty for this "computational optimality" is, of course, that Householder operations cannot be as deeply or efficiently parallelized.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/householder-transformation] As such Householder is preferred for dense matrices on sequential machines, whilst Givens is preferred on sparse matrices, and/or parallel machines.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] In numerical analysis, **inverse iteration** (also known as the *inverse power method*) is an iterative eigenvalue algorithm.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] It allows one to find an approximate eigenvector when an approximation to a corresponding eigenvalue is already known.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] The method is conceptually similar to the power method.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] It appears to have originally been developed to compute resonance frequencies in the field of structural mechanics.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] The inverse power iteration algorithm starts with an approximation $\mu$ for the eigenvalue corresponding to the desired eigenvector and a vector $b_{0}$ , either a randomly selected vector or an approximation to the eigenvector.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] where $C_{k}$ are some constants usually chosen as $C_{k}=\|(A-\mu I)^{-1}b_{k}\|.$ Since eigenvectors are defined up to multiplication by constant, the choice of $C_{k}$ can be arbitrary in theory; practical aspects of the choice of $C_{k}$ are discussed below.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] At every iteration, the vector $b_{k}$ is multiplied by the matrix $(A-\mu I)^{-1}$ and normalized.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] In practice, the method is used when a good approximation for the eigenvalue is known, and hence one needs only few (quite often just one) iterations.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] The basic idea of the power iteration is choosing an initial vector b (either an eigenvector approximation or a random vector) and iteratively calculating $Ab,A^{2}b,A^{3}b,...$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] Except for a set of zero measure, for any initial vector, the result will converge to an eigenvector corresponding to the dominant eigenvalue.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] The inverse iteration does the same for the matrix $(A-\mu I)^{-1}$ , so it converges to the eigenvector corresponding to the dominant eigenvalue of the matrix $(A-\mu I)^{-1}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] In particular, taking $\mu =0$ we see that $(A)^{-1}b_{k}$ converges to the eigenvector corresponding to the eigenvalue of $A^{-1}$ with the largest magnitude ${\frac {1}{\lambda _{N}}}$ and thus can be used to determine the smallest magnitude eigenvalue of A since they are inversely related.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] Let us analyze the rate of convergence of the method.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] This is a key formula for understanding the method's convergence.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] It shows that if $\mu$ is chosen close enough to some eigenvalue $\lambda$ , for example $\mu -\lambda =\epsilon$ each iteration will improve the accuracy $|\epsilon |/|\lambda +\epsilon -\lambda _{\mathrm {closest~to~} \lambda }|$ times.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] (We use that for small enough $\epsilon$ "closest to $\mu$ " and "closest to $\lambda$ " is the same.) For small enough $|\epsilon |$ it is approximately the same as $|\epsilon |/|\lambda -\lambda _{{\text{closest to }}\lambda }|$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] Hence if one is able to find $\mu$ , such that the $\epsilon$ will be small enough, then very few iterations may be satisfactory.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] The inverse iteration algorithm requires solving a linear system or calculation of the inverse matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] For non-structured matrices (not sparse, not Toeplitz,...) this requires $O(n^{3})$ operations.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] There are, however, multiple options for its implementation.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] emphasizing that to find the next approximation $b_{k+1}$ we may solve a system of linear equations.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] There are two options: one may choose an algorithm that solves a linear system, or one may calculate the inverse $(A-\mu I)^{-1}$ and then apply it to the vector.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] Both options have complexity *O*(*n*3), the exact number depends on the chosen method.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] The choice depends also on the number of iterations.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] Naively, if at each iteration one solves a linear system, the complexity will be *k* *O*(*n*3), where *k* is number of iterations; similarly, calculating the inverse matrix and applying it at each iteration is of complexity *k* *O*(*n*3).
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] Note, however, that if the eigenvalue estimate $\mu$ remains constant, then we may reduce the complexity to *O*(*n*3) + *k* *O*(*n*2) with either method.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] Calculating the inverse matrix once, and storing it to apply at each iteration is of complexity *O*(*n*3) + *k* *O*(*n*2).
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] Storing an LU decomposition of $(A-\mu I)$ and using forward and back substitution to solve the system of equations at each iteration is also of complexity *O*(*n*3) + *k* *O*(*n*2).
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] Inverting the matrix will typically have a greater initial cost, but lower cost at each iteration.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] Conversely, solving systems of linear equations will typically have a lesser initial cost, but require more operations for each iteration.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] If it is necessary to perform many iterations (or few iterations, but for many eigenvectors), then it might be wise to bring the matrix to the upper Hessenberg form first (for symmetric matrix this will be tridiagonal form).
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] Which costs ${\textstyle {\frac {10}{3}}n^{3}+O(n^{2})}$ arithmetic operations using a technique based on Householder reduction), with a finite sequence of orthogonal similarity transforms, somewhat like a two-sided QR decomposition.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] Solution of the system of linear equations for the tridiagonal matrix costs $O(n)$ operations, so the complexity grows like $O(n^{3})+kO(n)$ , where k is the iteration number, which is better than for the direct inversion.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] However, for few iterations such transformation may not be practical.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] Also transformation to the Hessenberg form involves square roots and the division operation, which are not universally supported by hardware.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] On general purpose processors (e.g. produced by Intel) the execution time of addition, multiplication and division is approximately equal.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] But on embedded and/or low energy consuming hardware (digital signal processors, FPGA, ASIC) division may not be supported by hardware, and so should be avoided.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] Choosing $C_{k}=2^{n_{k}}$ allows fast division without explicit hardware support, as division by a power of 2 may be implemented as either a bit shift (for fixed-point arithmetic) or subtraction of k from the exponent (for floating-point arithmetic).
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] When implementing the algorithm using fixed-point arithmetic, the choice of the constant $C_{k}$ is especially important.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] Small values will lead to fast growth of the norm of $b_{k}$ and to overflow; large values of $C_{k}$ will cause the vector $b_{k}$ to tend toward zero.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] The main application of the method is the situation when an approximation to an eigenvalue is found and one needs to find the corresponding approximate eigenvector.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] In such a situation the inverse iteration is the main and probably the only method to use.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] There are some situations where the method can be used by itself, however they are quite marginal.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] The dominant eigenvalue can be easily estimated for any matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] For any induced norm it is true that $\left\|A\right\|\geq |\lambda |,$ for any eigenvalue $\lambda$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] So taking the norm of the matrix as an approximate eigenvalue one can see that the method will converge to the dominant eigenvector.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] In some real-time applications one needs to find eigenvectors for matrices with a speed of millions of matrices per second.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] In such applications, typically the statistics of matrices is known in advance and one can take as an approximate eigenvalue the average eigenvalue for some large matrix sample.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] Better, one may calculate the mean ratio of the eigenvalues to the trace or the norm of the matrix and estimate the average eigenvalue as the trace or norm multiplied by the average value of that ratio.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] Clearly such a method can be used only with discretion and only when high precision is not critical.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/inverse-iteration] This approach of estimating an average eigenvalue can be combined with other methods to avoid excessively large error.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] In numerical linear algebra, the **Jacobi eigenvalue algorithm** is an iterative method for the calculation of the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of a real symmetric matrix (a process known as diagonalization).
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] It is named after Carl Gustav Jacob Jacobi, who first proposed the method in 1846, but it only became widely used in the 1950s with the advent of computers.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] This algorithm is inherently a dense matrix algorithm: it draws little or no advantage from being applied to a sparse matrix, and it will destroy sparseness by creating fill-in.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Similarly, it will not preserve structures such as being banded of the matrix on which it operates.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Let S be a symmetric matrix, and $G=G(i,j,\theta )$ be a Givens rotation matrix.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] In order to optimize this effect, *S**ij* should be the off-diagonal element with the largest absolute value, called the *pivot*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] The Jacobi eigenvalue method repeatedly performs rotations until the matrix becomes almost diagonal.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Then the elements in the diagonal are approximations of the (real) eigenvalues of *S*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] If $p=S_{kl}$ is a pivot element, then by definition $|S_{ij}|\leq |p|$ for $1\leq i,j\leq n,i\neq j$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Let $\Gamma (S)^{2}$ denote the sum of squares of all off-diagonal entries of S .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] A number of N Jacobi rotations is called a sweep; let $S^{\sigma }$ denote the result.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] that is, the sequence of sweeps converges at least linearly with a factor ‚âà $e^{1/2}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] However the following result of Sch√∂nhage yields locally quadratic convergence.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] To this end let *S* have *m* distinct eigenvalues $\lambda _{1},...,\lambda _{m}$ with multiplicities $\nu _{1},...,\nu _{m}$ and let *d* > 0 be the smallest distance of two different eigenvalues.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Each Givens rotation can be done in $O(n)$ steps when the pivot element *p* is known.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] However the search for *p* requires inspection of all *N* ‚âà ‚ÅÝ1/2‚ÅÝ *n*2 off-diagonal elements, which means this search dominates the overall complexity and pushes the computational complexity of a sweep in the classical Jacobi algorithm to $O(n^{4})$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Competing algorithms attain $O(n^{3})$ complexity for a full diagonalisation.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] We can reduce the complexity of finding the pivot element from O(*N*) to O(*n*) if we introduce an additional index array $m_{1},\,\dots \,,\,m_{n-1}$ with the property that $m_{i}$ is the index of the largest element in row *i*, (*i* = 1, ..., *n* ‚àí 1) of the current *S*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Then the indices of the pivot (*k*, *l*) must be one of the pairs $(i,m_{i})$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Also the updating of the index array can be done in O(*n*) average-case complexity: First, the maximum entry in the updated rows *k* and *l* can be found in O(*n*) steps.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] In the other rows *i*, only the entries in columns *k* and *l* change.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Looping over these rows, if $m_{i}$ is neither *k* nor *l*, it suffices to compare the old maximum at $m_{i}$ to the new entries and update $m_{i}$ if necessary.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] If $m_{i}$ should be equal to *k* or *l* and the corresponding entry decreased during the update, the maximum over row *i* has to be found from scratch in O(*n*) complexity.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] However, this will happen on average only once per rotation.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Thus, each rotation has O(*n*) and one sweep O(*n*3) average-case complexity, which is equivalent to one matrix multiplication.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Additionally the $m_{i}$ must be initialized before the process starts, which can be done in *n*2 steps.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Typically the Jacobi method converges within numerical precision after a small number of sweeps.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Note that multiple eigenvalues reduce the number of iterations since $N_{S}<N$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] An alternative approach is to forego the search entirely, and simply have each sweep pivot every off-diagonal element once, in some predetermined order.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] It has been shown that this *cyclic Jacobi* attains quadratic convergence, just like the classical Jacobi.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] The opportunity for parallelisation that is particular to Jacobi is based on combining cyclic Jacobi with the observation that Givens rotations for disjoint sets of indices commute, so that several can be applied in parallel.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Two processors can perform both rotations in parallel, because no matrix element is accessed for both.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Partitioning the set of index pairs of a sweep into classes that are pairwise disjoint is equivalent to partitioning the edge set of a complete graph into matchings, which is the same thing as edge colouring it; each colour class then becomes a round within the sweep.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] The minimal number of rounds is the chromatic index of the complete graph, and equals n for odd n but $n-1$ for even n .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] For even n one may create $n-1$ rounds $k=0,1,\dotsc ,n-2$ where a pair $\{i,j\}$ for $1\leqslant i<j\leqslant n-1$ goes into round $(i+j){\bmod {(}}n-1)$ and additionally a pair $\{i,n\}$ for $1\leqslant i\leqslant n-1$ goes into round $2i{\bmod {(}}n-1)$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] This brings the time complexity of a sweep down from $O(n^{3})$ to $O(n^{2})$ , if $n/2$ processors are available.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] A round would consist of each processor first calculating $(c,s)$ for its rotation, and then applying the rotation from the left (rotating between rows).
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Next, the processors synchronise before applying the transpose rotation from the right (rotating between columns), and finally synchronising again.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] A matrix element may be accessed by two processors during a round, but not by both during the same half of this round.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] Further parallelisation is possible by dividing the work for a single rotation between several processors, but that might be getting too fine-grained to be practical.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] The following algorithm is a description of the Jacobi method in math-like notation.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/jacobi-eigenvalue-algorithm] It calculates a vector *e* which contains the eigenvalues and a matrix *E* which contains the corresponding eigenvectors; that is, $e_{i}$ is an eigenvalue and the column $E_{i}$ an orthonormal eigenvector for $e_{i}$ , *i* = 1, ..., *n*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] The algorithm is also known as the **Von Mises iteration**.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] Power iteration is a very simple algorithm, but it may converge slowly.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] The most time-consuming operation of the algorithm is the multiplication of matrix A by a vector, so it is effective for a very large sparse matrix with appropriate implementation.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] The speed of convergence is like $(\lambda _{2}/\lambda _{1})^{k}$ where k is the number of iterations, and $\lambda _{1}$ and $\lambda _{2}$ are, respectively, the eigenvalue of largest absolute value and an eigenvalue of second-largest absolute value (see a later section).
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] In other words, convergence is exponential with base being the spectral gap.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] The power iteration algorithm starts with a vector $b_{0}$ , which may be an approximation to the dominant eigenvector or a random vector.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] So, at every iteration, the vector $b_{k}$ is multiplied by the matrix A and normalized.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] and the starting vector $b_{0}$ has a nonzero component in the direction of an eigenvector associated with the dominant eigenvalue, then a subsequence $\left(b_{k}\right)$ converges to an eigenvector associated with the dominant eigenvalue.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] Without the two assumptions above, the sequence $\left(b_{k}\right)$ does not necessarily converge.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] where $v_{1}$ is an eigenvector associated with the dominant eigenvalue, and $\|r_{k}\|\rightarrow 0$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] The presence of the term $e^{i\phi _{k}}$ implies that $\left(b_{k}\right)$ does not converge unless $e^{i\phi _{k}}=1$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] converges to the dominant eigenvalue (with Rayleigh quotient).
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] The vector $b_{k}$ converges to an associated eigenvector.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] Ideally, one should use the Rayleigh quotient in order to get the associated eigenvalue.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] This algorithm is used to calculate the *Google PageRank*.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] Let A be decomposed into its Jordan canonical form: $A=VJV^{-1}$ , where the first column of V is an eigenvector of A corresponding to the dominant eigenvalue $\lambda _{1}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] Since generically, the dominant eigenvalue of A is unique, the first Jordan block of J is the $1\times 1$ matrix $[\lambda _{1}],$ where $\lambda _{1}$ is the largest eigenvalue of A in magnitude.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] By assumption, $b_{0}$ has a nonzero component in the direction of the dominant eigenvector, so $c_{1}\neq 0$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] The sequence $\left(b_{k}\right)$ is bounded, so it contains a convergent subsequence.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] Note that the eigenvector corresponding to the dominant eigenvalue is only unique up to a scalar, so although the sequence $\left(b_{k}\right)$ may not converge, $b_{k}$ is nearly an eigenvector of A for large k .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] Suppose that $\lambda _{1}$ is the dominant eigenvalue, so that $|\lambda _{1}|>|\lambda _{j}|$ for all $j>1$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] If $b_{0}$ is chosen randomly (with uniform probability), then $c_{1}\neq 0$ with probability 1.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] Therefore, $b_{k}$ converges to (a multiple of) the eigenvector $v_{1}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] Thus, the method converges slowly if there is an eigenvalue close in magnitude to the dominant eigenvalue.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] Although the power iteration method approximates only one eigenvalue of a matrix, it remains useful for certain computational problems.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] For instance, Google uses it to calculate the PageRank of documents in their search engine, and Twitter uses it to show users recommendations of whom to follow.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] The power iteration method is especially suitable for sparse matrices, such as the web matrix, or as the matrix-free method that does not require storing the coefficient matrix A explicitly, but can instead access a function evaluating matrix-vector products $Ax$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] For non-symmetric matrices that are well-conditioned the power iteration method can outperform more complex Arnoldi iteration.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] For symmetric matrices, the power iteration method is rarely used, since its convergence speed can be easily increased without sacrificing the small cost per iteration; see, e.g., Lanczos iteration and LOBPCG.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] Some of the more advanced eigenvalue algorithms can be understood as variations of the power iteration.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] For instance, the inverse iteration method applies power iteration to the matrix $A^{-1}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] Other algorithms look at the whole subspace generated by the vectors $b_{k}$ .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] This subspace is known as the Krylov subspace.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] It can be computed by Arnoldi iteration or Lanczos iteration.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/power-iteration] Gram iteration is a super-linear and deterministic method to compute the largest eigenpair.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/rayleigh-quotient-iteration] Rayleigh quotient iteration is an iterative method, that is, it delivers a sequence of approximate solutions that converges to a true solution in the limit.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/rayleigh-quotient-iteration] Very rapid convergence is guaranteed and no more than a few iterations are needed in practice to obtain a reasonable approximation.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/rayleigh-quotient-iteration] The Rayleigh quotient iteration algorithm converges cubically for Hermitian or symmetric matrices, given an initial vector that is sufficiently close to an eigenvector of the matrix that is being analyzed.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/rayleigh-quotient-iteration] The algorithm is very similar to inverse iteration, but replaces the estimated eigenvalue at the end of each iteration with the Rayleigh quotient.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/rayleigh-quotient-iteration] Begin by choosing some value $\mu _{0}$ as an initial eigenvalue guess for the Hermitian matrix A .
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/rayleigh-quotient-iteration] An initial vector $b_{0}$ must also be supplied as initial eigenvector guess.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/rayleigh-quotient-iteration] To compute more than one eigenvalue, the algorithm can be combined with a deflation technique.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/rayleigh-quotient-iteration] Note that for very small problems it is beneficial to replace the matrix inverse with the adjugate, which will yield the same iteration because it is equal to the inverse up to an irrelevant scale (the inverse of the determinant, specifically).
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/rayleigh-quotient-iteration] The adjugate is easier to compute explicitly than the inverse (though the inverse is easier to apply to a vector for problems that aren't small), and is more numerically sound because it remains well defined as the eigenvalue converges.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/rayleigh-quotient-iteration] from which the cubic convergence is evident.
[src:eigenvalue-algorithms/rayleigh-quotient-iteration] The following is a simple implementation of the algorithm in Octave.
